mained vibrant at this period, contrary to the common idea that print had by this stage destroyed traditional minstrelsy. The author shows that under the patronage of Edward Stanley, earl of Derby, and his son, from one of the most important aristocratic families in England, Sheale recited and collected ballads and travelled to and from London to market them. Amongst his repertoire was the famous Chevy Chase, which Sir Philip Sidney said moved his heart "more than witha trumpet". Sheale also composed his own verse, including a lament on being robbed of 60 on his way to London; the poem is reproduced in this volume. ANDREW TAYLOR lectures in the Department of English, University of Ottawa.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aMinstrelszEnglandxHistoryy16th century. 0aMusiczEnglandy16th centuryxHistory and criticism. 4aBibliography & Manuscripts. 4aEarly Modern History. 4aEnglish & American Literature. 4aMusic. 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  aBallads.  aminstrels.  amusic.  asongs.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978184615863640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781846158636423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781846158636/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles